<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials `Doubt' Enforcement of Super 301 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1802135694 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 17 Feb 94 
Evening Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1802135694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] With regard to U.S. moves for the revival of the 
Super 301 provision, the Japanese Government observes that 
"because it is President Clinton's campaign pledge, there is a 
great possibility of the revival," (as stated by an official at 
the Ministry of International Trade and Industry). However, 
some Japanese Government officials doubt whether the Super 301 
provision will be actually invoked as a retaliatory measure in 
the wake of the recent breakdown in the Japan-U.S. economic 
framework talks. 
  The Super 301 provision requires the U.S. Government to 
consider sanctions based on an annual report on trade barriers 
which is issued every spring. For this reason, the revival of 
the Super 301 provision does not mean an immediate retaliatory 
action. In 1989, the U.S. Government studied a possibility of 
imposing sanctions against Japan over disputes concerning 
satellites, supercomputers, and timber products. However, 
sanctions were avoided because an agreement was reached in the 
Japan-U.S. negotiations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

