<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Voluntary Targets Suggested To Reduce Surplus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1802063494 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 18 
Feb 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1802063494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 18 February Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] Discussing what Japan should do in view of the 
breakdown in the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks, a senior 
Ministry of International Trade and Industry [MITI] official 
said on 17 February: "We should review and augment the Five 
Year Economic Plan for a Better Quality of Life and the 430 
trillion yen plan for public investment by this fall, and 
clarify our position from the next fiscal year." He indicated 
that Japan should clearly manifest its efforts to reduce the 
trade surplus through the expansion of domestic demand in order 
to win the understanding of the United States. 
  The official also touched on the ratio of the current 
accounts surplus to GNP (2.8 percent) in the government's 
economic forecast for fiscal 1994, saying: "If we can come up 
with a figure for the ratio of the surplus to GNP in the process 
of reviewing the economic programs, we will be able to predict 
the course of the Japanese economy from fiscal 1995." He, in 
effect, suggested that Japan should draw up a voluntary plan for 
reducing the current accounts surplus. This was the first time 
a senior government official has referred to the need to set a 
macroeconomic target. Such a remark seemed to represent an 
effort to meet U.S. expectations by setting a "voluntary target" 
at the macroeconomic level through the inclusion of a ratio for 
current accounts surplus in Japanese economic plans. 
  However, the senior official stressed that this ratio "is 
absolutely a voluntary figure to be shown to the people; it is 
not a target to fulfill for the United States." 
  Last July, at the beginning of the framework talks, the 
United States demanded the setting of macroeconomic numerical 
targets, such as the ratio of current accounts surplus, but 
Japan refused. This eventually led to an agreement to draw up 
"objective criteria" in specific sectors, such as automobiles 
and auto parts, and so forth. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

