<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI Vice Minister Concerned About Strong Yen </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1502144494 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 15 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 7 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1502144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hideaki Kumano, administrative vice minister of 
international trade and industry, expressed deep concern 14 
February about the recent steep rise in the yen's value. He 
said: "I am greatly concerned about the impact of the yen's 
appreciation on the economy. The economic recession has lasted 
for four years. However, the economy -- far from being 
revitalized for the first time in four years -- will be cooled 
down by the recent strong yen." 
  Vice Minister Kumano pointed out: "The yen's appreciation 
will largely worsen profits of export-oriented companies. In 
the short-term the exchange rate will have a negative impact on 
people's incomes rather than a favorable effect on commodity 
prices." 
  He stressed that if economic conditions in Japan 
deteriorated 
further due to growing pressure for the yen to appreciate, it 
would have an unfavorable effect on the world economy as well as 
on the Japanese economy. 

</TEXT>

