<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDPJ Not in Favor of New Party for Election </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1702102694 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 17 Feb 
94 Morning Edition p2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1702102694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Wataru Kubo, secretary general of the Social 
Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ], delivered a lecture at the 
Foreign Correspondents Club on 16 February. Referring to a 
possible political realignment in the future, Kubo said: "I 
think it is impossible to merge coalition parties into one based 
on the theory of nation building, behind which there is an idea 
of establishing a two-conservative-party system advocated by 
Ichiro Ozawa, chief secretary of Shinseito [Japan Renewal 
Party]." In this way, he indicated that the SDPJ would not 
agree to a plan proposed by Shinseito and Komeito that coalition 
parties should merge and form "a new party" to contest the next 
House of Representatives election as a single party. 
  Kubo stressed: "I share the same view with Hokkaido Governor 
Yokomichi. We think that the coalition parties should cooperate 
in tackling urgent issues and that those who aim to establish a 
similar government should cooperate." In a question and answer 
session after the lecture, Kubo clarified differences between 
his idea and Ozawa's, saying: "My idea about the nation is 
different from Ozawa's. I think we also have differing opinions 
on Japan's international contributions and the Constitution." 
  With regard to the issue of reshuffling the cabinet, Kubo 
said: "If the government is considering a cabinet reshuffle to 
remove a certain minister, it will lose its centripetal force." 

</TEXT>

