<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ichikawa Reiterates Support for Cabinet Reshuffle </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1802061394 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 18 
Feb 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1802061394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 18 February Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] In an interview with MAINICHI SHIMBUN on 17 
February, Yuichi Ichikawa, secretary general of Komeito, 
reiterated his support for Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's 
plan to reshuffle the cabinet. He also said: "Objectively 
speaking, Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura was the one 
who created the cabinet reshuffle problem." He indicated the 
cabinet reshuffle issue had nothing to do with a realignment of 
the political world, but was caused by Takemura's inappropriate 
behavior as chief cabinet secretary. 
  Commenting on Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] 
Secretary General Wataru Kubo's view that the future 
administration should be a coalition under a "trilateral 
structure" consisting of the "new conservative forces," "new 
reformist forces," and Liberal Democratic Party, Ichikawa said: 
"Such a setup will not be suitable under the heiritsu system 
[electoral system combining single-seat constituencies with 
proportional representation]." 
  Commenting further on a suggestion by the SDPJ and Chairman 
Akira Yamagishi of Rengo [Japanese Trade Union Confederation] 
that "social democracy" or "liberalism" should serve as the 
unifying force of the political regime, Ichikawa said: "That is 
a question for the distant future. We should unite and fight in 
the election as an extension of cooperation in reform efforts 
(such as Diet reform and deregulation)." He expressed his 
belief that the present coalition framework should develop into 
a new-new party. He maintained: "It is the SDPJ which should 
undertake self-reform first in the areas of foreign policy, 
defense, energy, and taxation, to make itself a proper key 
component of the political regime." 

</TEXT>

