<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegation Discusses Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1402185294 Prague CTK in English 1554 GMT 12 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1402185294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bangkok Feb 12 (CTK) -- Czech Deputy Premier and 
Finance Minister Ivan Kocarnik and Foreign Minister Josef 
Zieleniec signed today, along with the Thai Foreign Minister 
Prasong Sunsiri, a Czech-Thai trade agreement, agreements on 
protection and support of investments, on prevention of double 
taxation, and on cooperation of the two countries' Foreign 
Ministries. 
  Kocarnik and Zieleniec are members of the Czech delegation 
currently visiting Thailand and headed by Czech President Vaclav 
Havel. 
  Zieleniec said that by signing the agreements, the two 
parties wanted to indicate that their relations were "more 
intensive and surpassed the phase of acquainting each other." 
  At the Czech visitors' meeting with Thai representatives 
today, the discussion focused on a future cooperation between 
the countries associated in the Central European Free Trade 
Agreement (CEFTA), comprising the Czech Republic, Hungary, 
Poland and Slovakia, and the Asian Free Trade Agreement (AFTA), 
of which Thailand is member. 
  "The agreement on this sort of cooperation is very important 
for us, since Asian countries are known for their 
protectionism," Zieleniec said. 
  Kocarnik informed journalists that the Thai partners were 
well acquainted with the economic situation in the Czech 
Republic, which they found "unambiguously the best of all" 
post-communist countries. 
  "The premier (Chuan Likphai) even said he was sorry about 
the 
shortage of (Czech-made) Skoda cars which Thailand had 
imported," Kocarnik said. He added that Thai bankers intended 
to establish a bank in Prague which would promote mutual trade. 
  Likphai gave today a ceremonial dinner to honour Havel. At 
the dinner, Havel briefly outlined possibilities of the 
Czech-Thai cooperation on third markets. 
  Havel today toured some of Bangkok's monuments, including 
the 
statue of Emerald Buddha, Thailand's most adored Buddha. 
  On Sunday [13 February] he is to visit the ancient city of 
Ayutthaia, former Thai capital. 

</TEXT>

