<H3> <TI>   Kumagai Responds to Clinton's 17 Feb Remarks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1802034294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0334 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1802034294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 18 KYODO -- Japan should keep calm over 
the aggressive U.S. trade stance, Minister of International 
Trade and Industry Hiroshi Kumagai said Friday [18 February]. 
He made the comment in response to U.S. President Bill 
Clinton's statement on Thursday that the U.S. will pursue an 
"much more aggressive policy" to push Japanese markets open. 
  Clinton said he would try "different things" to achieve the 
goal of opening Japan's markets. 
  Kumagai told reporters after a regular cabinet meeting that 
the U.S. has often adopted such an attitude, even against old 
allies like Britain, when trade talks were deadlocked. 

</TEXT>

