<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Reveals Rice Production Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1902024294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0205 GMT 19 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1902024294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 19 (YONHAP) -- To make its rice farming 
structure fit the agricultural market opening, the government 
has mapped out a comprehensive plan to cut rice costs and 
improve quality. The Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries 
Ministry said Saturday it had set this year's rice output at 
5.08 million tons (37.2 million sok), down 4.6 percent from 5.35 
million tons in 1993, a bad crop year due to cool summer weather. 
  Farmland was estimated to drop 21,000 hectares to 1.11 
million hectares based on the past five-year average decrease, 
with each 300 pyong (990 square meters) producing 456 kilograms 
for this year's output quota. As a result, in view of the 1993 
provisional record of 96.9 percent, the rice self-sufficiency 
rate is expected to be under 100 percent in 1994 (estimated at 
89.1 percent) and 1995 (95.9 percent), but Korea will attain 100 
percent self-sufficiency in edible rice by 2001 The ministry 
said it had revised this year's rice policy to put quality above 
quantity in the wake of the conclusion of the Uruguay Round 
trade agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

